addXMIValue

public Value addXMIValue(java.lang.String name,
                         java.lang.Object value)
If there is no Value object with the given name, create one, set its name to the given name and its value to the given value. If there is a Value object with the given name, add the given value to the Value object.

If a new Value is created, its type is set as follows. If the value is java.lang.String, the type of the new Value is set to BASIC. If the value is an XMIObject, the type of the Value is set to REFERENCE. Otherwise, the type of the Value is UNSPECIFIED.

If you need to create a new Value whose type is ENUM, CONTAINER, or CONTAIN, you need to use void addXMIValue(String name, Object value, int type).

Specified by:
addXMIValue in interface XMIObject
Parameters:
name - The XMI name of the value.
value - The value of the Value object to set or add.
Returns:
The Value object that was created or set.

addXMIValue

public Value addXMIValue(java.lang.String name,
                         java.lang.Object value,
                         int type)
If there is no Value object with the given name, create one, set its name to the given name, its value to the given value, and its type to the given type. If there is a Value object with the given name, add the given value to the Value object. If the given value is a string, and the value of the existing Value object is a string, make the value a collection that contains the two strings. Do a similar thing if the value is XMIObject. If the given value is a Collection and the existing value is a Collection, add each item of the given value to the existing value.
Specified by:
addXMIValue in interface XMIObject
Parameters:
name - The XMI name of the value.
value - The value of the Value object to set or add.
type - The type of the new Value object, if one is created.

If there is a Value object with the given name, set its value to the given value; this value replaces the previous value of the Value object. If there is no Value object with the given name, invoke addXMIValue(name, value, type).

If there is already a Value object with the given name, the type parameter is not used.

toString

public java.lang.String toString()
The string representation of an XMI object appears as follows:

XMIObject xmiName label id uuid [ owner ]

The xmiName is the XMI name of the object, the label is added if it is not null, the id is added if it is not null, the uuid is added if it is not null, and the owner of the object is added and enclosed in [] if it is not null.

Overrides:
toString in class DataImpl
Returns:
"XMIObject" + the XMI name + the label, if there is one, + the id if there is one, + the uuid if there is one, plus [ owner ] if there is an owner.
